headline: {'main': 'RECORD OF AMUSEMENTS.; LOCAL AFFAIRS. WALLACK\'S THEATRE. FIFTH AVENUE THEATRE. BOOTH\'S THEATRE. Miss Neilson, who has drawn very large audiences to Booth\'s Theatre since Monday, acts at that house throughout this week. "Amy Robsart" is to be the play until Friday, when Miss Neilson is to profit by the performance; "The Hunchback" and the "balcony scene" from "Romeoand Juliet," with Mr. H.J. Montague asRomeo, are to be given on this occasion. Saturday, there will be a matinee, and, in the evening entertainment, the lady will bid farewell, for a year atleast to the American public. Miss Neilson sails for Europe on May 13. On May 11 Miss Clara Morris begins an engagement at Booth\'s. She is first to appear in "Evadne," and is to have the co-operation of Mr. George Clarke. abstract: The Atlantic Club of Brooklyn was badly defeated by the new Hartford nine on the Union Grounds yesterday. The game was the third of the series for the professional championship, and was witnessed by about 800 persons. Play was commenced at 3:40 P.M. with Mr. Martin, of the Nameless Club, as umpire. In the first inning the Hartfords were easily disposed of without scoring.

abstract: Only a moderate acquaintance with the history of the Democratic Party for the last twenty-five years would seem to be sufficient to satisfy any one that it can not be trusted. For obstinate bad character that party has a well-established reputation.
